ce:section.ce:para:
Changes in ΔP and the recovery factor were determined to evaluate the effect of the two proposed flooding fluids (containing 0.5 wt% GQDs and 2000-ppm polymer at low and high salinity) in carbonate cores. In the first step, brine (salty water) was flooded into the core samples. After injections of approximately 0.6 pore volume (PV) (Fig. 11
                        ) and 1.8 PV (Fig. 12
                        ), ΔP reached approximately 236 and 253 psi in cores B and C, respectively. Next, the proposed flooding fluids were flooded. Because they have very high viscosity caused by the presence of the polymer, a significant increase in ΔP, compared with that in the previous step, was observed. The high ΔP value in the porous medium is observed in liquids that have high elasticity, thus improving the macroscopic sweep efficiency [85], which increases the recovery of residual oil. This increment was close to a flat plateau when the breakthrough occurred in the core samples and tended to decrease during the third flooding step; this was attributed to the proposed flooding fluids finding a facile production route throughout the core. The flooding fluid in the third step was brine, which has a lower viscosity than the other fluids used. During the flooding steps, salt water flooding can be continued, but only 2 or 3 PV is typically injected because there is no economic justification for exceeding this amount; therefore, in the post-flush step, salt water is injected into the core until oil is no longer ejected [28].
